        Gazumping in Queensland: What It Is and What Sellers and Buyers Can Do
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Gazumping is legal in Queensland until a contract is signed. Here is what it actually means, when sellers face the decision, and how buyers can protect themselves.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Gazumping is one of those property terms that generates a disproportionate amount of anxiety, partly because it sounds more dramatic than it usually is and partly because it occupies an uncomfortable space between what is legal and what many people consider fair. In Queensland, understanding exactly when and how it can occur, and what both parties can do about it, helps sellers make clear decisions and helps buyers manage their exposure before a signed contract is in place.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What gazumping actually means</h2>
      <p>Gazumping occurs when a seller accepts a verbal offer or reaches an in-principle agreement with one buyer, and then accepts a higher offer from a different buyer before a signed contract has been exchanged. The first buyer, who believed they had secured the property, finds out the property has been sold to someone else for more money.</p>

      <p>It is important to distinguish gazumping from other situations that buyers sometimes describe with the same term. A seller withdrawing from negotiations before any offer is accepted is not gazumping. A seller receiving competing offers at auction and selling to the highest bidder is not gazumping. Gazumping specifically involves a buyer who believed they had a deal, only to have the seller accept a higher competing offer before the paperwork was executed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why it is legal in Queensland</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, a property transaction only becomes legally binding once a contract of sale has been signed by both the buyer and the seller and the signed document has been exchanged between the parties. A verbal agreement, a handshake, an email exchange, or an agent's verbal confirmation that an offer has been accepted does not create a legally enforceable obligation on the seller to proceed.</p>

      <p>This is the same legal framework that applies across most of Australia. Property contracts are required to be in writing to be enforceable, and the exchange of signed copies is the point at which both parties become bound. Until that moment, either party can, in theory, walk away. In practice, buyers are at greater risk from this exposure than sellers because buyers who have done due diligence, arranged finance pre-approval, and been told their offer is accepted have often invested significant time and sometimes money before the contract is signed.</p>

      <p>Queensland's Property Law Act governs these transactions and does not provide a mechanism for buyers to enforce a verbal agreement to sell. The legal exposure for buyers before exchange is real, which is why the standard professional advice is to move to a signed contract as quickly as possible once an offer is accepted in principle.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The ethical and reputational considerations for sellers</h2>
      <p>Just because something is legal does not make it straightforward. Sellers who gazump a buyer face reputational consequences that are worth weighing against the financial benefit of accepting a higher offer. In a local market like Brisbane's inner east, where word travels through social networks, school communities and suburb Facebook groups, being known as a vendor who backed out of a verbal agreement to take more money creates a narrative that can follow you. Agents also talk, and sellers who are known to have accepted verbal agreements and then moved to a higher offer may find it affects their relationship with the agent and the agency's referral network.</p>

      <p>There are also practical consequences for the buyer who is gazumped. If that buyer has incurred costs, such as a building and pest inspection, legal review fees, or travel for multiple inspections, they have a grievance that is understandable even if they have no legal remedy. Sellers who are aware that a buyer has incurred real expense based on a verbal agreement carry a more substantial ethical weight when deciding whether to accept a competing offer.</p>

      <p>None of this means a seller should never accept a better offer before a contract is signed. But it does mean the decision warrants more than a purely financial calculation. The question a reasonable seller should ask is whether the benefit of the higher offer is proportionate to the harm done to the first buyer and the reputational cost of how the decision will be perceived.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When accepting a higher offer before exchange makes sense</h2>
      <p>There are circumstances where accepting a higher offer before a contract is signed is clearly the right call, even accounting for the ethical considerations. If the original offer was accepted before due diligence was complete and a materially higher offer arrives from a buyer who is ready to proceed immediately, the financial difference to the seller can be significant and the harm to the first buyer is limited if no contract conditions have been agreed and no costs have been incurred.</p>

      <p>The situation is different when a seller has been through a detailed negotiation with the first buyer, agreed to conditions, indicated to the buyer's solicitor that they are ready to exchange, and then moves to a competing offer. The further into the process the original negotiation has progressed, the more weight the ethical considerations carry. A seller who does this should expect the first buyer to feel aggrieved and to share that experience.</p>

      <p>In practice, most sellers in Brisbane's inner-east market do not face this dilemma. Private treaty campaigns typically work through one buyer at a time or through a structured multi-offer process, and the majority of negotiations move from accepted offer to signed contract within a few days. The risk of a competing offer materialising in that window is low but not zero, particularly in active markets where a property attracts high interest but only one buyer makes an offer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How agents manage competing offers transparently</h2>
      <p>A good agent will not put a seller in the position of having to gazump a buyer if the campaign is managed well from the start. When multiple buyers are interested and the agent is aware of competing interest, the professional approach is to run a multi-offer or best-and-final process rather than accepting a verbal agreement from one buyer and then fielding a higher offer from another.</p>

      <p>A multi-offer process notifies all interested parties that the seller is considering offers and invites each to put forward their best offer by a specified time. This approach surfaces genuine competition, gives all buyers the same information, and puts the seller in a position to make one decision rather than a sequence of decisions. It also removes the appearance of dealing in bad faith, because no buyer has been told their offer is accepted before the process concludes.</p>

      <p>Sellers should ask their agent how they intend to handle competing buyer interest if it arises. An agent who has thought about this and has a clear process will handle it more professionally than one who manages each buyer interaction in isolation and creates situations where gazumping becomes the path of least resistance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the multi-offer process looks like in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane's inner-east market, multi-offer situations are most common in the lower to middle segment of the market where buyer competition is highest. The process typically works as follows: the agent identifies that two or more buyers are in a position to make an offer, notifies each buyer that the property is in a multi-offer situation, and requests that each buyer submit their best offer by a nominated time, usually within 24 to 48 hours.</p>

      <p>Buyers are generally not told what the competing offers are, though they may be given a sense of where interest sits relative to the guide. The seller then reviews all offers and selects the one that best meets their criteria, which may include price but also conditions, settlement timeline, and the buyer's ability to proceed without lengthy finance conditions.</p>

      <p>For sellers, this process is straightforward. For buyers, it requires making a decision about what the property is genuinely worth to them without knowing what they are competing against. Buyers who approach a multi-offer scenario with a clear sense of their ceiling and offer at or near it tend to perform better in this environment than those who try to win by the smallest possible margin over a figure they have guessed at.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How buyers can protect themselves from being gazumped</h2>
      <p>The most effective protection against gazumping is speed. Once an offer is accepted in principle, a buyer's priority is to move to a signed contract as quickly as possible. This means having your solicitor or conveyancer briefed and ready before you make an offer, not after. A conveyancer who has already reviewed the contract conditions and is ready to advise you quickly can turn around a signed contract in 24 to 48 hours, which dramatically reduces the window in which a competing offer can emerge.</p>

      <p>Buyers should also be clear about their conditions from the start. A buyer who accepts the standard contract conditions and is ready to proceed to exchange quickly is in a stronger position than one who is negotiating conditions when a competing offer arrives. Sellers and agents will often give priority to a buyer who can demonstrate they are ready to exchange, even at a marginally lower price, over one who is still working through conditions days after the verbal acceptance.</p>

      <p>Some buyers try to negotiate an exclusivity period with the seller, during which the seller agrees not to accept competing offers while the contract is being finalised. Sellers are not obliged to agree to this and many will not, but in some circumstances, particularly where the buyer has incurred or is about to incur significant due diligence costs, a reasonable seller may agree to a short exclusivity window of 24 to 48 hours. Any such agreement should be in writing, though it is worth noting that even a written exclusivity agreement may not be enforceable in the same way as a property contract.</p>

      <p>Ultimately, the best protection a buyer has against gazumping is an agent and a seller who manage the process professionally and transparently. Asking the agent directly how they handle competing offers, and what their process is if another buyer comes forward after your offer is accepted, will tell you a great deal about whether you are working with someone who prioritises the integrity of the process.</p>

